        <h1>Power Encoding</h1>
        <h2>Definition</h2>
        <p>Given a <b><i>number</i></b> such that </p>
        <ul>
            <li><b><i>number = +-{base, power, remainder}</i></b></li>
            <li>such that <b><i>number = +-(base<sup>power</sup> + remainder)</i></b></li>
            <li>and <b><i>base</i></b>, <b><i>power</i></b>, <b><i>remainder</i></b> are <b><i>numbers</i></b> or <b><i>i</i></b></li>
            <li>where <b><i>i<sup>2</sup> = - 1</i></b></li>
        </ul>
<!--
        <p>Power encoded numbers are length encoded. In other words you can read a power encoded number from a bit stream without prior knowledge of the numbers size.</p>
        <p>Power encoded numbers can be compared for equality, less then and greater then without the need to decode.</p>

        <p>For a javascript implementation refer to <a href="Power Encoding.js">Power Encoding.js</a></p>
        </br>
        <p>This example writes 100 numbers to a stream, displaying the binary and base 10 encoding and then reads them from the stream.</p>
        <p><pre id="displayScript"></pre></p>
        </br>
        <script type="text/javascript" id="script" >
document.getElementById("displayScript").innerHTML = document.getElementById("script").text;

var allNumbersStream = new BitStream();
for (var x = 0; x < 100; x++) {
    var y = new PowerEncoding(x);
    var stream = new BitStream();
    y.write(stream);
    y.write(allNumbersStream);
    document.writeln(x + " : " + stream.array.join("") + " : " + stream.toNumber() + "</br>");
}

var read = allNumbersStream.openRead();
while (!read.isEnd) {
    var y = PowerEncoding.read(PowerEncoding.number, read);
    document.writeln(y.decode() + "</br>");
}

        </script>
        </br>
